pageContext.claim: “China produces a car and they sell it into the United States, and they have a very small 2.5% tax, which, to a large extent they don't even pay. On the other hand we make a car and sell it into China and they charge 25 percent. So it's 25 percent versus 2.5%, and that's the way the deal is: no good, and no good for us.”
pageContext.analysis: China imposed a 15 percent tariff on cars as of July 1, down from 25 percent. General Motors sells more cars in China (3.9 million) than in the United States (3 million) and saw its China business grow 13 percent in 2016.
